body:
### Environment

Node version: v16.13.0
npm version: v8.1.0
Local ESLint version: v8.9.0 (Currently used)
Global ESLint version: Not found
Operating System: darwin


### What parser are you using?

@typescript-eslint/parser

### What did you do?

<details>
<summary>Configuration</summary>

```
module.exports = {
	env: {
		browser: true,
		es2021: true,
		node: true
	},
	extends: [
		'eslint:recommended',
		'plugin:@typescript-eslint/recommended'
	],
	parser: '@typescript-eslint/parser',
	parserOptions: {
		ecmaVersion: 'latest',
		sourceType: 'module'
	},
	plugins: [
		'@typescript-eslint'
	],
	rules: {
	}
}
```
</details>

```js
const a = new RegExp('\t');
  // expected: error; actual: error
const b = new RegExp('\\t');
  // expected: no error; actual: no error
const c = new RegExp('\u0009');
  // expected: error; actual: error
const d = new RegExp('\\u0009');
  // expected: no error; actual: error
const e = new RegExp('\x09');
  // expected: error; actual: error
const f = new RegExp('\\x09');
  // expected: no error; actual: error
```


### What did you expect to happen?

I expected no errors for the lines defining `d` and `f`. The comments in the reproduction example show my expectations and the observed behavior.

### What actually happened?

I am seeing unexpected errors for the lines defining `d` and `f` (lines 7 and 11):

```
   1:22  error  Unexpected control character(s) in regular expression: \x09  no-control-regex
   5:22  error  Unexpected control character(s) in regular expression: \x09  no-control-regex
   7:22  error  Unexpected control character(s) in regular expression: \x09  no-control-regex
   9:22  error  Unexpected control character(s) in regular expression: \x09  no-control-regex
  11:22  error  Unexpected control character(s) in regular expression: \x09  no-control-regex
```

The errors for the lines 1, 5 and 9 are expected.

### Participation

- [ ] I am willing to submit a pull request for this issue.

### Additional comments

As a rationale of  the rule https://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-control-regex says: "These characters are rarely used in JavaScript strings so a regular expression containing these characters is most likely a mistake".

Note that the strings `'\\u0009'` and `'\\x09'` do not contain control characters: `'\\u0009' === String.fromCharCode(0x5C, 0x75, 0x30, 0x30, 0x30, 0x39)` and `'\\x09' === String.fromCharCode(0x5C, 0x78, 0x30, 0x39)`.
